                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d854">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/12691.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Brazilian Minister</gloss> to Mexico.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-01">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 1, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>190. A telegram from our Consul at Saltillo calls attention to the difference
                    which the Constitutionalists make between an armistice and the suspension of
                    military operations. General Carranza’s Secretary for Foreign Affairs, Fabela,
                    informs him that when Provisional President Carbajal’s envoys arrive with proper
                    credentials and authority, military operations will be suspended as
                    announced.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
